05638nam a22007935i 9780748646333DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222011stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486463337 a10.1515/97807486463332doi  a(DE-B1597)616366  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aPR1225 7aLCO0090002bisacsh04a821.9121 aLyall, Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Edinburgh Companion to Hugh MacDiarmid /cScott Lyall, Margery Palmer McCulloch. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Companions to Scottish Literature : ECSL00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations and Notes -- tSeries Editors’ Preface -- tBrief Biography of Hugh MacDiarmid -- tIntroduction -- t1. MacDiarmid and International Modernism -- tMacDiarmid’s Language -- t3. C. M. Grieve/Hugh MacDiarmid, Editor and Essayist -- t4. Transcending the Thistle in A Drunk Man and Cencrastus -- t5. MacDiarmid, Communism and the Poetry of Commitment -- t6. MacDiarmid and Ecology -- t7. The Use of Science in MacDiarmid’s Later Poetry -- t8. Hugh MacDiarmid’s (Un)making of the Modern Scottish Nation -- t9. Hugh MacDiarmid: The Impossible Persona -- t10. Transatlantic MacDiarmid -- t11. MacDiarmid’s Ambitions, Legacy and Reputation -- tEndnotes -- tFurther Reading -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe only full-length companion available to this distinctive and challenging Scottish poet By using previously uncollected creative and discursive writings, this international group of contributors presents a vital updating of MacDiarmid scholarship. They bring fresh insights to major poems such as A Drunk Man Looks at the Thistle, To Circumjack Cencrastus and In Memoriam James Joyce, and offer new political, ecological and science-based readings in relation to MacDiarmid's work from the 1930s. They also discuss his experimental short fiction in Annals of the Five Senses, the autobiographical Lucky Poet, and a representative selection of his essays and journalism. They assess MacDiarmid's legacy and reputation in Scotland and beyond, placing his poetry within the context of international modernism.Key FeaturesLinks MacDiarmid's work and influence to recent writings on national identity, transnationalism, postcolonialism and modernity versus traditionProvides close readings of the formal detail of texts and new readings in ecological and science-based contextsContributes to a re-drawing of the map of literary modernismContributors include Louisa Gairn (Helsinki), Alan Riach (Glasgow University), Carla Sassi (Verona University), Jeffrey Skoblow (Southern Illinois University), and Michael H. Whitworth (Oxford University).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aGairn, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrieve, Dorian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyall, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer McCulloch, Margery, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPalmer McCulloch, Margery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiach, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSassi, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkoblow, Jef